segments.text: Once about Prairie View.
Prairie View.
I said, I think I made the appointment because I wanted to talk with him.
I was quite prepared to do what we could to help political science at Prairie View.
And I told Dr. Williams at the moment, the Department of Political Science at Prairie View is headed by a man with a master's degree in education.
who is scared of President Thomas.
They will not, Thomas will not allow their students to come to us for an MPA.
One of their assistants in the admissions office wanted to come.
I'm sure Thomas said no.
I had a faculty member, a woman, who'd been on the faculty
A&M.
I can't give you her name offhand.
Black woman.
In terms of affirmative action, you can't be more affirmative.
And she was good.
She now has a PhD and is teaching, I think, in Louisiana Southern, maybe.
And I said, what can be done about this?
And I'll never forget William's part.
What we really ought to do is close it up.
Did you see the morning paper in the Houston op-ed?
Yes.
They're a law and medical school.
Because I thought, in terms of management, neither Texas Southern or Prairie View have a very good record.
The more recent generals have been somewhat of an improvement.
Let's see, Dr. Williams and Dr. Calhoun move out from university-level administration in the mid-'70s, six and seven, and Jarvis Miller and Mac Prescott take over.
Did that change anything for you as a department head?
Not a lot.
Prescott was very helpful because it was under him the MPA went through.
and he was a guiding piece and so on.
Environmental design wanted in on it, several people wanted to cut in on it by that point and he held the line and we went with the design that it had been.
Jarvis Miller I had no connection with except we all remember when he said everybody will be in their offices from eight to five.
and what he thought was going on.
He apparently had seen some people jogging at odd hours, and there was interesting reactions to that.
But no, no special problem.
The school was growing so rapidly and all the rest, we were hitting the problem of large classes.
And how did you all face that?
with large classes.
But taught by?
I insisted.
Oh, one thing my predecessor had done was to do 206 and 7 by lectures and assistant professors, upper division by associate professors, and graduate work by full professors.
I said, I'm sorry, this is coming to a screeching halt.
And everybody will at least have one section of 206 and 7.
And I took an honors course in 206 myself as my one teaching job for the moment, my way of illustration.
But all sections were taught by faculty.
Yes.
I'll say with a few exceptions, I did give some graduate assistants a section after they'd been here as graduate students at least one year.
Can you share any goofy, loony, only at A&M-like events that you coped with as a department head?

Well, I was told that if I hadn't been coming, that the departmental graduate students, of whom there were three or four on the highly liberal side, would have hung rubber rudder in effigy that spring, which would have been an interesting problem to inherit.
No, I don't know anything startling.
Any jokes that got played on any faculty member by the students or anything like that?
Not that I can think of.
We did have one faculty member harassing the lady graduate students who finally left.
Did you ever have any midnight calls by anybody about anything supposedly happening in the department?
One funny one involves Linda.
I get a call that Linda would like to come talk to me, and she is the wife of Ralph Hambrick, who is an assistant professor, very good.
We weren't sure at first.
No, I'm sorry.
Hamrick's wife is not named Linda.
Hamrick's wife is calling, sir, like Mary or something.
She wants to talk to him.
Well, we're over across the road over there, and she comes to our house to talk.
She said,
Oh, dear, I've got problems.
My husband is going with somebody else.
And if it just weren't for Linda, I thought, oh, God, Linda is Gary Holder's wife.
For God's sake, where are we into it?
Well, it turned out Linda is also the name of one of our secretaries.
So I kept a straight face to find out
what, Linda, are we talking about?
It turned out that it was the...
The secretary.
Our departmental secretary.
And eventually, Ralph and his wife divorce, and he marries Linda.
And Ralph is now at the University of Richmond, and full professor, and Linda is his wife.
But it was a little uncertain for a bit whose wife.
Did anyone ever, from outside the appropriate scope of the department, did anyone try to ever intervene to meddle?
An A&M former student, a board member, a politician?
Anybody try to influence an admission or a grade?
No more.
You're talking about the senator?
Yeah, Bull of the Brassets.
Well, I got word from the dean that one of my lectures, Dan is now with the
controller's office in Florida, I think, Dan Burns, had made comments about political corruption in Texas.
And Moore had made the cover of Time at one time in connection with the scandals prior to Ben Barnes and the rest of it.
and that Moore was after Dan Burns.
Well, I went to Benton, and I said, what?
Well, Benton said, we've got a clipping file over in the library.
And he got me all the clippings about Moore's insurance scandal activities, into which he was up to his ass in problems.
and made a Xerox of them for me.
And I sent that file about Moore to Maxwell.
And I never heard another word.
Now, what went on, I don't know.
Did you ever get a complaint from a parent or anyone about us?
Yes, on Elias Thermos for teaching revolution.
Because on his reading list is Das Kapital and several other books.
They're not required reading, but on the reading list.
And I called Elias and I said, what gives?
He said, well, we discussed revolution, of course, and the political theory.
I said, OK. Don't worry, Elias.
I think I can take care of this.
And I said,
We have a policy in political science, particularly in light of our situation in A&M and the military, that we have a policy that it is absolutely essential that you know your enemy.
I never heard any more.
Did anyone ever try to...
Excuse me.
Don't forget...
OK, I was about to ask, did anyone ever try to, from outside the appropriate scope of the department, ever try to influence a grade that someone received or might receive?
Not really.
I never had any particular pressure.
I handled a great appeal once, which caused me to give some thought to the A&M judicial system.
I was acting head one Christmas vacation for Kirkpatrick.
And a great appeal came in from a student and his parents because if it stood, he wasn't going to graduate.
And complaints on George Edwards.
who is an assistant professor, I think at the time, maybe associate, and on the examination grade.
I discussed it with them and they accepted.
I said, I will have that paper read by
And we discussed who, and I said, what about Professor Benton?
Yes, he said, that would be appropriate.
So I had Professor Benton read the paper.
And Benton gave it a D. Now, I said, that is so close to the grade that you got, I will not change the grade.
He appealed to the judicial committee, and the judicial committee overturned the thing without consideration.
And the student judicial committee, and there's some faculty on it too, did not support the faculty.
And I figured there are two problems with it.
One is there's no way for faculty to appeal that kind of thing.
And second, there's no training in the student judicial body in proper
evidential procedures.

But correct me if I'm wrong, in your years I didn't hear you say that some legislator, some self-appointed important Aggie called you up to get so-and-so passed or get so-and-so admitted, no outside information.
If you were looking back on those... Next to nothing.
I can't think of anything on that.
Looking back over those years in the department, which department members do you think deserve the greatest praise?
I'm not going to ask you the negative.
If you were giving pats on the back, who would get the most?
I think, in many ways, Gary Holder.
Why?
Explain.
I don't disagree with you.
I'm just asking you to elaborate.
He was a first-rate teacher.
He did not publish much.
He is now doing more.
And he has handled the student advising function for years.
drive most people to drink.
I always advocated that this kind of service function, somebody has to do.
And Warren Dixon was not publishing much, but he was doing the laboratory.
developing that.
And I said to the faculty, or to the dean, I said, I want to give tenure to both Dixon and Holder who they haven't published much for their service and their things.
I said, a department's got to have a few people who are willing to do the sub-administrative work that is absolutely essential.
And
they were willing to pick up things.
It was at some cost to them.
I didn't care whether they were, some other people are going to write and so on, but they were both very good at what they did.
Typist, this is an editorial note.
When Gary Halter was a sophomore, he was in one of my classes,
And it was my policy then, my wife and I would have each of my classes over to our house for a reception and to get acquainted near the end of the semester.

And on this particular evening, this young sophomore transfer student from Wichita Falls, Gary Halter, stayed after everybody else left and told me he was thinking about dropping out of school, wasn't sure he was making much progress.
Did I have any advice for him?
We chatted a long time and I tried to persuade him that I thought he had
many of the capabilities that a good faculty member needed.
And I urged him, since he said he was short of money, go back home to Wichita Falls and take another year at Midwestern University that he had attended as a freshman.
Since then, he has told me that that advice that evening was rather important to him, because at that point, he didn't know where else to turn.
So let's add that as an editorial note here.
Any other faculty?
Yes, Arnold Bedlitz.
I hired Arnold around 75.

I had $9,000 left in the budget, and I called down to Houston to see who they had, and Arnold was available, and I told Arnold, almost sight unseen, I said, I've got $9,000 if you want to come for that for the year.
Why, you can have it.
And he came.
He's been here ever since.
And I think done a superb job.
And after three or four years, I could begin to close the salary gap that was there.
Was it good that you, as the department head, had the authority to go out and do the looking?
Was that better than having a big search committee?
Well, I always had the authority and kept it for lectures or instructors.
Assistant professors, we had committees.
Let me do some quick things for teaching that I had to do.
Outside of the department, were there any other department heads that were good allies for the department?
Well, John Pearson, I mentioned in business, worked together very nicely.
We worked together very well with Samson in, what engineering was he in?
Chuck Samson?
Chuck Samson.
I see, civil?
Civil engineering.
Civil engineering had the first
training program for city managers in the United States, as far as we know.
And they were helpful in providing engineering for non-engineers and some special work in street engineering in cities, etc.
And Samson and I functioned
very well.
The sociology and anthropology were in Bolton a bit, and we worked out the laboratory thing among us.
Those have been...
In hindsight, can you think of any missed opportunities for the department or the campus during those years?
Looking back now... No, I don't think as much.
Were there any proposals you sent forward relating to the department that got scuttled?
No, the main one that was scuttled for a while was the MPA.
But it's simply because of the coordinating board.
Is there any advice?
Let's make believe now you're anointed to be the advisor to the department, to the college, to the university.
What advice would you give today to each of those levels?
What should political science be aspiring to do today?
Well, I'm in general sympathy with the department, except political science departments generally have got a problem.
For as I'm concerned, the field of public law is going into decline, as there was a period when public administration was.
The department does not have
It has Judith Bair, who's superb.
She'd just gotten a prize from ASPA, American Political Science Association, for a book on women and law.
And we had originally Benton and Woods for de-emphasis in public law, which strikes me as idiocy.
And we have nobody in international law.
You kind of get that problem.
And the behavioral number stuff is very heavy, but I don't have any great problem with that.
So that would be the main criticism I would have of the department.
What about at the university level?
What advice would you give today's leadership, if any?
Well, the Vision 2000 is interesting.
I was just taking a look at it a while back because I'm working on a set of bylaws for the Bush School.
As my wife tells friends occasionally, he does bylaws.
I offered to play with it.
I'm a parliamentarian for the Senate and so on.
And I did the bylaws for the College of Liberal Arts.
There has been a tendency, Maxwell was the last dean who really
emphasized faculty participation in the entire operation of the college.
We had a monthly faculty meeting which handled the business, the academic business of the college.
The Department of Law proposal, it went through the entire faculty.
The committee system backing it up and recommendations, et cetera.
Your history man who succeeded, and I cannot think of his name, the man who now dean.
Oh, came from Oklahoma.
Yeah.
And he's now at Telluride, Colorado.
I think so.
Then the fellow who came out of psychology, who's now at Maryland, the next dean.
He was here for several years.
Okay, I can't think of it either.
But he was here, and he ended Maxwell's faculty for an elected small policy committee.
And I think it shot communications through the college.
And ever since Williams, I have not sensed any interest in the administration up above that there be
really much faculty governance.
Now this creation of the faculty senate by our historian.
Frank Vandiver.
Vandiver is an exception in that.
And because it's got authority to, it can't.
override the board or the president, but it's got authority to talk about any damn thing it wants to, really.
It has almost any connection to the academic work.
And we have not had regular faculty meetings.
There's one faculty meeting a year, I think, in the college, which is a pro forma thing for making awards.
And the Vision 2000 doesn't do much more.
There's a sentence about governance, and there's a backhanded reference to faculty in the last sentence of that.
Do you think that in the Vision 2020, the goal of A&M moving up within the next 20 years to be one of the top 10 public institutions in the country, do you think that is an appropriate goal?
Is it reachable?
It's reachable if anybody will put money to it.
And I...
It depends on the...
Top echelon.
And I view part of his, I view the president as very good.
I view the next layers as highly questionable.
I'm nodding in agreement with you on that.
Let's move to the Bush Library.
When did you become aware that there was going to be an effort by Texas A&M to attract the presidential library of George Bush?
Oh, I wasn't terribly aware of it.
Let's see, we began to get discussions of this
Because very early, and I'm working on a history of the Bush School.
And very early on, within six months of Hal Booty's visit to Bush in, what the hell is it, 80 or 81 or 79?
Oh, when he's elected?
Yeah.
Oh, he's elected in 88.
He's elected.
That's right.
He's elected, excuse me, but he isn't in the office yet.
That's right.
He calls on him late in November 1988.
Yeah, okay.
Because within two or three months of that, the school is part of the deal.
And having been involved with the MPA program, we're immediately...
brought on it as to how does this fit.
So I'm aware there are negotiations fairly early.
It's a bit of a surprise.
As Lewis Newman, who was on the committee, talked to Rotary not long after the decision was made, he said,
He was present in Houston when Rice and Houston and we made presentations.
And he said it was very odd Kathy Whitmer was making one for Houston, I think.
But it was in general terms as if they both took it for granted it would be one of them, but did not have an awful lot in concrete
where A&M had the land, had a school in mind, had the driveway named, and it was already on the drawing boards exactly where the hell it would be.
Can you think of any misstep A&M made in that process?
No.
I don't know of any.
Who are the people, as far as you know?
The main one, I've heard him say this.
He said, after all, Yale hugged me in effigy twice.
And I've reported that to friends.
Which A&M people deserve pats on the back most for the Bush Library being here?
Al Booney and, oh, another board member who'd been, I can't remember.
John Lindsay?
Lindsay.
And then the A&M administration handled it well, didn't they?
Yes, the OX business dean who then got chatted to him.
And Perry Atkinson was the chancellor.
Perry Atkinson, chancellor of...
At no point appearing to be either uninterested or obstructed.
Now, were people in the real world of academia called upon in an appropriate fashion as the A&M plans are being formulated?
Well, the Senate was called on.
